{"title_page": "Victory Eagle", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Victory Eagle.jpg|thumb|right|300px|''The Victory Eagle'' at the [[University of Kansas]]]] -->\n'''''The Victory Eagle''''' is a bronze sculpture designed to honor the veterans and casualties of [[World War I]]. Although the artist is not known, noted [[ornithologist]]s Thomas Roberts and Otto Widmann consulted on its development.<ref name=bridgeport/> The statue depicts an eagle with its wings spread protectively over two young eaglets in a nest, symbolizing the United States' protection of its citizens.<ref name=bridgeport/><ref name=citizen/> Although they were originally mounted on stone bases, all have since been moved from their original locations.<ref name=VEK>{{cite web | url=http://theplaygroundtrail.com/Playground/Victoy_Eagles.html | title=Victory Eagles of Kansas | website=The Playground Trail | last1=Whiteley | first1=Lee | last2=Whiteley | first2=Jane | access-date=August 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nProduced in the early 1920s, the monuments were meant to mark each [[border|county line]] along the [[Victory Highway]] as it crossed the United States. In the original design, two eagles would mark each crossing&mdash;one on each side of the road&mdash;to form a chain of monuments from coast to coast. At the terminals in San Francisco and New York, huge groups of eagles would be mounted on bases along with bronze statues of a soldier, a sailor, and a [[Red Cross]] nurse.<ref name=citizen>{{cite news | title=Eagle Group Sign for Every County | newspaper=Washington Citizen | location=Washington, Missouri | date=October 20, 1922 | page=1}}</ref> However, the statues had to be paid for through private funding, and the plan eventually fell apart when the [[Great Depression]] began.<ref name=sun2013/> Only six monuments were ever installed.\n\n==Present locations==\n*[[Lawrence, Kansas]] (originally at the Douglas\u2013Leavenworth County line, rededicated at [[Dyche Hall, University of Kansas]] in 1982)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=136115283O5OJ.3343&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!332321~!3&ri=2&aspect | title=The Victory Eagle (sculpture) | website=Art Inventories Catalog | publisher=Smithsonian Institution | access-date=August 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://hmofriends.org/landmarks/eagle.shtml | title=The Victory Eagle | website=Historic Mount Oread Friends | access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Topeka, Kansas]] in Gage Park (relocated from the Shawnee\u2013Douglas County line)<ref name=VEK/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.washburn.edu/cas/art/cyoho/archive/AroundTopeka/victoryeagle/ | title=Victory Highway World War I Veterans Memorial | first=Carol | last=Yoho | date=2007 | access-date=August 16, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Wamego, Kansas]]<ref name=VEK/><ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.kshs.org/publicat/history/2006autumn_trout.pdf | title=Forgotten Reminders: Kansas World War I Memorials | journal=Kansas History: A Journal of the Central Plains | volume=29 | date=Autumn 2006 | pages=200\u2013215 | first=Steven | last=Trout | access-date=August 16, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Truckee, California]] (relocated from the California\u2013Nevada border)<ref name=bridgeport>{{cite news | title=Dedication of war memorial by American Legion | date=May 19, 1928 | url=https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%205/Bridgeport%20California%20Chronical%20Union/Bridgeport%20California%20Cronical%20Union%201927-1930.pdf/Bridgeport%20California%20Cronical%20Union%201927-1930%20-%200274.PDF | work=Bridgeport Chronicle-Union | location=Bridgeport, California | access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=sun2013>{{cite news | title=Rare World War I monument back on display in Truckee | url=http://www.sierrasun.com/news/7324723-113/monument-truckee-town-hall | first=Margaret | last=Moran | newspaper=Sierra Sun | location=Truckee, California | date=July 15, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914192011/http://www.sierrasun.com/News/7324723-113/monument-truckee-town-hall | archive-date=September 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3030494/victory_eagle_to_surmount_highway_shaft/ | title=Victory Eagle to Surmount Highway Shaft | newspaper=Oakland Tribune | date=May 16, 1928 | page=5 | access-date=August 16, 2015 | via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.tahoedailytribune.com/article/20121130/NEWS/121139991 | title=A town 'victory': Truckee's World War I Eagle Monument to be restored | first=Margaret | last=Moran | newspaper=Sierra Sun | location=Truckee, California | date=November 30, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812235608/http://www.tahoedailytribune.com/article/20121130/NEWS/121139991 | archive-date=August 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url=https://www.truckeehistory.org/uploads/5/1/9/2/51923135/2015.03_echoes_march_2015_issue1.pdf | title=Victory Highway Eagle Monument Rededication | journal=Echoes from the Past | date=March 2015 | page=2 | publisher=Truckee Donner Historical Society | access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Sacramento, California]]<ref name=VEK/>\n*[[Antioch, California]] (originally in [[Oakley, California]]; moved in 1976)<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2008/12/26/oakley-aims-to-reclaim-long-lost-statue-2/ | title=Oakley aims to reclaim long lost statue | first=Jonathan | last=Lockett | newspaper=East County Times | location=Antioch, California | date=December 26, 2008 | access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2009/04/17/oakley-fails-in-quest-for-world-war-i-memorial/ | title=Oakley fails in quest for World War I memorial | first=Jonathan | last=Lockett | newspaper=East County Times | location=Antioch, California | date=April 17, 2009 | access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2012/11/28/oakley-collecting-funds-for-veterans-memorial/ | title=Oakley collecting funds for veterans memorial | first=Rowena | last=Coetsee | newspaper=Contra Costa Times | location=Walnut Creek, California | date=November 28, 2012 | access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2014/11/04/oakley-to-unveil-victory-eagle-at-veterans-day-event/ | title=Oakley to unveil 'Victory Eagle' at Veterans Day event | first=Katrina | last=Cameron | newspaper=Contra Costa Times | location=Walnut Creek, California | date=November 4, 2014 | access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{coord missing|California}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Victory Eagle}}\n[[Category:Military monuments and memorials in the United States]]\n[[Category:1920s sculptures]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Kansas]]\n[[Category:World War I memorials in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in California]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of birds in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bronze sculptures in California]]\n[[Category:1920s establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Statues in California]]\n[[Category:Animal sculptures in California]]\n[[Category:Animal sculptures in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in California]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Statues in Kansas]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Victory Eagle.jpg|thumb|right|300px|''The Victory Eagle'' at the [[University of Kansas]]]] -->\n'''''The Victory Eagle''''' is a bronze sculpture designed to honor the veterans and casualties of [[World War I]]. Although the artist is not known, noted [[ornithologist]]s Thomas Roberts and Otto Widmann consulted on its development.<ref name=bridgeport>{{cite news | title=Dedication of war memorial by American Legion | date=May 19, 1928 | url=https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%205/Bridgeport%20California%20Chronical%20Union/Bridgeport%20California%20Cronical%20Union%201927-1930.pdf/Bridgeport%20California%20Cronical%20Union%201927-1930%20-%200274.PDF | work=Bridgeport Chronicle-Union | location=Bridgeport, California | access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> The statue depicts an eagle with its wings spread protectively over two young eaglets in a nest, symbolizing the United States' protection of its citizens.<ref name=citizen/> Although they were originally mounted on stone bases, all have since been moved from their original locations.<ref name=VEK>{{cite web | url=http://theplaygroundtrail.com/Playground/Victoy_Eagles.html | title=Victory Eagles of Kansas | website=The Playground Trail | last1=Whiteley | first1=Lee | last2=Whiteley | first2=Jane | access-date=August 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nProduced in the early 1920s, the monuments were meant to mark each [[border|county line]] along the [[Victory Highway]] as it crossed the United States. In the original design, two eagles would mark each crossing&mdash;one on each side of the road&mdash;to form a chain of monuments from coast to coast. At the terminals in San Francisco and New York, huge groups of eagles would be mounted on bases along with bronze statues of a soldier, a sailor, and a [[Red Cross]] nurse.<ref name=citizen>{{cite news | title=Eagle Group Sign for Every County | newspaper=Washington Citizen | location=Washington, Missouri | date=October 20, 1922 | page=1}}</ref> However, the statues had to be paid for through private funding, and the plan eventually fell apart when the [[Great Depression]] began.<ref name=sun2013/> Only six monuments were ever installed.\n\n==Present locations==\n*[[Lawrence, Kansas]] (originally at the Douglas\u2013Leavenworth County line, rededicated at [[Dyche Hall, University of Kansas]] in 1982)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=136115283O5OJ.3343&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!332321~!