{"title_page": "Chris Sparling", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Chris Sparling\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1977|03|21}}\n| birth_place               = [[Providence, Rhode Island]], United States\n| death_date                = \n| death_place               = \n| other_names               = \n| occupation                = [[Screenwriter]], [[film director]], [[actor]]\n| spouse                    = Kerri Morrone Sparling \n| partner                   = \n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Chris Sparling''' (born March 21, 1977) is an American screenwriter, director, and actor from Providence, Rhode Island.\n\n==Career==\nAfter writing, directing, and acting in several low-budget independent films,<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2133655/ Chris Sparling, IMDB page]</ref> Sparling found mainstream success when his feature length screenplay [[Buried (film)|''Buried'']] was purchased by producer [[Peter Safran]]. Spanish director [[Rodrigo Cort\u00e9s]] and actor [[Ryan Reynolds]] worked on the project.\n\nThe film premiered at the [[2010 Sundance Film Festival]] to high critical praise<ref>[http://www.filmmakermagazine.com/news/2010/01/running-out-of-air-penning-midnight-movie-buried-by-melissa-silvestri/ RUNNING OUT OF AIR: PENNING MIDNIGHT MOVIE \u201cBURIED\u201d]</ref><ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/buried/ Buried - Rotten Tomatoes]</ref> and was eventually sold to [[Lionsgate Films]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/news/ni1464625/ Sundance: Ryan Reynolds' 'Buried' sold to Lionsgate].</ref>  After later playing additional film festivals worldwide\u2014including the [[Toronto International Film Festival]], as well as winning the M\u00e9li\u00e8s d'Or Award<ref>[http://sitgesfilmfestival.com/eng/noticies/?id=1003027 Buried wins the M\u00e9li\u00e8s d'Or]</ref> at the [[Sitges Film Festival]]\u2014it received a limited theatrical release in September 2010, earning over $18 million worldwide.<ref>[http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=buried.htm Buried  - Box Office Mojo]</ref> The film was later released on DVD in January 2011.\n\nSparling was awarded Best Original Screenplay by the [[National Board of Review Awards 2010|2010 National Board of Review]] for ''Buried'' and the film was selected as on the 10 Best Independent Films of 2010.  He also won a [[25th Goya Awards|Goya Award]] in 2011 for Best Original Screenplay,<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/arts/film/story/2011/02/14/goya-award-winners.html Bardem among Spain's Goya winners - Kudos for Buried]</ref> and he was nominated for a Gaudi Award<ref>[http://www.catalannewsagency.com/news/culture/catalan-oscars-be-celebrated-tonight Catalan Oscars to be celebrated tonight] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708123534/http://www.catalannewsagency.com/news/culture/catalan-oscars-be-celebrated-tonight |date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref> as well in the same category.\n\nSparling later wrote the script ''ATM'',<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1603257/ ATM, IMDB page]</ref> a suspense thriller produced by Peter Safran and shot in Winnipeg, Manitoba in the fall of 2010 <ref>[http://www.slashfilm.com/chris-sparlings-atm-details-revealed/ Chris Sparling\u2019s ATM Details Revealed]</ref> and released in 2012 by IFC Films.  He also wrote ''Reincarnate'' for producer [[M. Night Shyamalan]], the second film of a three-part series known as [[Devil (2010 film)|The Night Chronicles]].<ref>[http://www.deadline.com/2010/09/m-night-shyamalan-mrc-bedeviled-with-reincarnate/ MRC And M. Night Shyamalan 'Reincarnate']</ref><ref>[http://collider.com/daniel-stamm-m-night-shyamalan-night-chronicles-reincarnate/49044/ Daniel Stamm to Helm Next M. Night Shyamalan \u201cNight Chronicles\u201d Picture, REINCARNATE]</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Sparling was hired by Warner Brothers and [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] to adapt the crime novel ''Blood on Snow'', written by author [[Jo Nesb\u00f8]]. This same year, his original screenplay, ''[[The Sea of Trees]]'', went into production, starring [[Matthew McConaughey]], [[Naomi Watts]], and [[Ken Watanabe]], and directed by [[Gus Van Sant]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'Alessandro|first1=Anthony|title=\u2018Sea Of Trees\u2019 With Matthew McConaughey Begins Lensing In Massachusetts, Japan|url=http://deadline.com/2014/07/sea-of-trees-with-matthew-mcconaughey-begins-lensing-in-massachusetts-japan-812190/|website=Deadline|date=30 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' named Sparling one of \"10 Screenwriters to Watch\" in its November 2014 issue.<ref>[http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/82778/atticus-institute-image-gallery-possesses-internet/ The Atticus Institute Image Gallery Possesses the Internet]</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Whistler Film Festival Spotlights Variety's 10 Screenwriters to watch|url=http://firstweekendclub.ca/site12/read/fwc-blog/item/whistler-film-festival-spotlights-variety-s-10-screenwriters-to-watch|access-date=2015-02-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213170120/http://firstweekendclub.ca/site12/read/fwc-blog/item/whistler-film-festival-spotlights-variety-s-10-screenwriters-to-watch|archive-date=2015-02-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> Two months later, Sparling's horror-thriller film ''[[The Atticus Institute]]'', which he both wrote and directed, was released by Anchor Bay Films. Universal Pictures will distribute the film internationally.\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''An Uzi at the Alamo'' (2005, also director)\n* ''Balance'' (2007, also director)\n* ''[[Buried (film)|Buried]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[ATM (2012 film)|ATM]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[The Atticus Institute]]'' (2015, also director)\n* ''[[The Sea of Trees]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Mercy (2016 film)|Mercy]]'' (2016, also director)\n* ''[[The Warning (2018 film)|The Warning]]'' (2018, adapted screenplay)\n* ''[[Down a Dark Hall (film)|Down a Dark Hall]]'' (2018, adapted screenplay)\n* ''[[Greenland (film)|Greenland]]'' (2020)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Goya Award for Best Original Screenplay}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|2133655}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sparling, Chris}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Actors from Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Writers from Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Rhode Island]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Chris Sparling\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1977|03|21}}\n| birth_place               = [[Providence, Rhode Island]], United States\n| death_date                = \n| death_place               = \n| other_names               = \n| occupation                = [[Screenwriter]], [[film director]], [[actor]]\n| spouse                    = Kerri Morrone Sparling \n| partner                   = \n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Chris Sparling''' (born March 21, 1977) is an American screenwriter, director, and actor from Providence, Rhode Island. He is married to Kerri Morrone Sparling, author of the diabetes blog ''Six Until Me''.\n\n==Career==\nAfter writing, directing, and acting in several low-budget independent films,<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2133655/ Chris Sparling, IMDB page]</ref> Sparling found mainstream success when his feature length screenplay [[Buried (film)|''Buried'']] was purchased by producer [[Peter Safran]]. Spanish director [[Rodrigo Cort\u00e9s]] and actor [[Ryan Reynolds]] worked on the project.\n\nThe film premiered at the [[2010 Sundance Film Festival]] to high critical praise<ref>[http://www.filmmakermagazine.com/news/2010/01/running-out-of-air-penning-midnight-movie-buried-by-melissa-silvestri/ RUNNING OUT OF AIR: PENNING MIDNIGHT MOVIE \u201cBURIED\u201d]</ref><ref>[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/buried/ Buried - Rotten Tomatoes]</ref> and was eventually sold to [[Lionsgate Films]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/news/ni1464625/ Sundance: Ryan Reynolds' 'Buried' sold to Lionsgate].</ref>  After later playing additional film festivals worldwide\u2014including the [[Toronto International Film Festival]], as well as winning the M\u00e9li\u00e8s d'Or Award<ref>[http://sitgesfilmfestival.com/eng/noticies/?id=1003027 Buried wins the M\u00e9li\u00e8s d'Or]</ref> at the [[Sitges Film Festival]]\u2014it received a limited theatrical release in September 2010, earning over $18 million worldwide.<ref>[http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=buried.htm Buried  - Box Office Mojo]</ref> The film was later released on DVD in January 2011.\n\nSparling was awarded Best Original Screenplay by the [[National Board of Review Awards 2010|2010 National Board of Review]] for ''Buried'' and the film was selected as on the 10 Best Independent Films of 2010.  He also won a [[25th Goya Awards|Goya Award]] in 2011 for Best Original Screenplay,<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/arts/film/story/2011/02/14/goya-award-winners.html Bardem among Spain's Goya winners - Kudos for Buried]</ref> and he was nominated for a Gaudi Award<ref>[http://www.catalannewsagency.com/news/culture/catalan-oscars-be-celebrated-tonight Catalan Oscars to be celebrated tonight] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708123534/http://www.catalannewsagency.com/news/culture/catalan-oscars-be-celebrated-tonight |date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref> as well in the same category.\n\nSparling later wrote the script ''ATM'',<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1603257/ ATM, IMDB page]</ref> a suspense thriller produced by Peter Safran and shot in Winnipeg, Manitoba in the fall of 2010 <ref>[http://www.slashfilm.com/chris-sparlings-atm-details-revealed/ Chris Sparling\u2019s ATM Details Revealed]</ref> and released in 2012 by IFC Films.  He also wrote ''Reincarnate'' for producer [[M. Night Shyamalan]], the second film of a three-part series known as [[Devil (2010 film)|The Night Chronicles]].<ref>[http://www.deadline.com/2010/09/m-night-shyamalan-mrc-bedeviled-with-reincarnate/ MRC And M. Night Shyamalan 'Reincarnate']</ref><ref>[http://collider.com/daniel-stamm-m-night-shyamalan-night-chronicles-reincarnate/49044/ Daniel Stamm to Helm Next M. Night Shyamalan \u201cNight Chronicles\u201d Picture, REINCARNATE]</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Sparling was hired by Warner Brothers and [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] to adapt the crime novel ''Blood on Snow'', written by author [[Jo Nesb\u00f8]]. This same year, his original screenplay, ''[[The Sea of Trees]]'', went into production, starring [[Matthew McConaughey]], [[Naomi Watts]], and [[Ken Watanabe]], and directed by [[Gus Van Sant]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'Alessandro|first1=Anthony|title=\u2018Sea Of Trees\u2019 With Matthew McConaughey Begins Lensing In Massachusetts, Japan|url=http://deadline.com/2014/07/sea-of-trees-with-matthew-mcconaughey-begins-lensing-in-massachusetts-japan-812190/|website=Deadline|date=30 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' named Sparling one of \"10 Screenwriters to Watch\" in its November 2014 issue.<ref>[http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/82778/atticus-institute-image-gallery-possesses-internet/ The Atticus Institute Image Gallery Possesses the Internet]</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Whistler Film Festival Spotlights Variety's 10 Screenwriters to watch|url=http://firstweekendclub.ca/site12/read/fwc-blog/item/whistler-film-festival-spotlights-variety-s-10-screenwriters-to-watch|access-date=2015-02-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213170120/http://firstweekendclub.ca/site12/read/fwc-blog/item/whistler-film-festival-spotlights-variety-s-10-screenwriters-to-watch|archive-date=2015-02-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> Two months later, Sparling's horror-thriller film ''[[The Atticus Institute]]'', which he both wrote and directed, was released by Anchor Bay Films. Universal Pictures will distribute the film internationally.\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''An Uzi at the Alamo'' (2005, also director)\n* ''Balance'' (2007, also director)\n* ''[[Buried (film)|Buried]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[ATM (2012 film)|ATM]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[The Atticus Institute]]'' (2015, also director)\n* ''[[The Sea of Trees]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Mercy (2016 film)|Mercy]]'' (2016, also director)\n* ''[[The Warning (2018 film)|The Warning]]'' (2018, adapted screenplay)\n* ''[[Down a Dark Hall (film)|Down a Dark Hall]]'' (2018, adapted screenplay)\n* ''[[Greenland (film)|Greenland]]'' (2020)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Goya Award for Best Original Screenplay}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|2133655}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sparling, Chris}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Actors from Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Writers from Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Rhode Island]]\n", "name_user": "Lrapsc", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed marital information for privacy reasons.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Sparling"}
{"title_page": "OnlyFans", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|British subscription-only content service}}\n{{Infobox dot-com company\n| name = OnlyFans, Inc.\n| logo = OnlyFans logo 2.jpg\n| screenshot = \n| screenshot_size = <!-- default 300px -->\n| caption = \n| screenshot_alt = is\n| collapsible = no\n| collapsetext = \n| type = Membership platform\n| language = English\n| num_users = 20 million registered users\n| CEO = {{unbulleted list|Timothy Stokely}}\n| location_city = [[London]]\n| location_country = United Kingdom\n| launch_date = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2016}}\n| founder = {{unbulleted list|Timothy Stokely}}\n| alexa = {{increase}} 1,157 {{small|{{nowrap|(Global, {{as of|2020|04|15|alt= April 2020}})}}}}<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url= https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/onlyfans.com | title= Onlyfans.com Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic | publisher= [[Alexa Internet]] |accessdate= 15 April 2020}}</ref>\n| current_status = Active\n}}\n[[File:Logo of OnlyFans since the launch in 2016.png|thumb|Logo of OnlyFans since the launch in 2016]]\n'''OnlyFans''' is a [[social media]] service based in [[London]], United Kingdom. Creators run a paid [[Subscription service|subscription content service]], with ways for them to build relationships and provide exclusive content to their [[subscribers]], or \"[[fan (person)|fan]]s\". \n\nIt is popular in the [[adult entertainment]] industry,<ref name=\"nythow\" /> but also hosts content creators from other genres such as [[physical fitness]] experts<ref name=\":1\" /> and other creators who post regularly online. It allows content creators to receive funding directly from their fans on a monthly basis as well as on tips and the [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) feature.<ref name=\"mediapack\">{{cite nonews|last=|first=|url=|title=English: OnlyFans media pack|date=12 February 2019|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}{{full citation needed|date=February 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' commended OnlyFans for helping change adult entertainment work by giving control back to the performers to earn money for the content they create.<ref name=\"nythow\">{{Cite news|last1=Bernstein|first1=Jacob|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/09/style/onlyfans-porn-stars.html|title=How OnlyFans Changed Sex Work Forever|date=9 February 2019|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|access-date=22 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Business model ==\nOnlyFans deliberately lacks restrictive content policy and permits users to share revealing or completely nude pictures of themselves in exchange for a monthly membership fee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pandoramodeling.com/only-fans-for-adult-video-chat-models/|title=OnlyFans Guide For Adult Video Chat Models|website=Pandora Modeling|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref> 80% of the fees collected for each feed go to the content creator, and the remaining 20% percent go to OnlyFans.<ref name=\"nythow\"/> After merchant and processing fees, the company's share is around 12%.<ref name=\"nythow\" />\n\n== History ==\nOnlyFans was launched in 2016 as a website for social media performers to allow their followers to subscribe for a monthly fee to see clips and photos.\nLittle is known about the parent company, Fenix International Limited.<ref name=\"nythow\" />\n\nAs of February 2020, the site has 20 million [[registered user]]s and claims to have paid out $400 million to its 200,000 content creators.<ref name=\"fandeck\">{{cite news |title=English: OnlyFans brand deck |url= |date=8 November 2019}}{{full citation needed|date=February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable creators ===\nIn 2017, [[Courtney Stodden]] urged followers to subscribe to her updates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/courtney-stodden-starts-charging-randy-11493289|title=Courtney Stodden starts charging randy fans to see her nudes|last=Kindon|first=Frances|last2=Duff|first2=Seamus|date=9 November 2017|website=mirror|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref> In 2018 [[Megan Barton Hanson]], a participant in the reality television series [[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 4)|''Love Island'']], posted naked videos of herself online for a monthly subscription.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/showbiz/celebrity-news/love-islands-megan-barton-hanson-12675723|title=Newbie Megan poses for naked videos in an online subscription site|last=Martin|first=Laura|date=10 June 2018|website=irishmirror|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, 20-year-old American Kaylen Ward raised more than $1 million in contributions to [[Charitable organization|charity]] during the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|wild bushfires in Australia]]. OnlyFans teamed with her for their first partnership for a charitable cause.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/the-goods/2020/1/8/21056863/australia-fires-nudes-charity-porn| title=Nude photos raised over $1 million for the Australia fires|website=VOX|access-date=9 January 2020}}</ref> This started a trend with some OnlyFans creators who have been raising money through their accounts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/07/style/kaylen-ward-donations-australia-fires.html| title=Donate $10 to Australia, Get a Nude Photo|website=New York Times|access-date=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Usage ==\nThe website is commonly used by both [[Amateur pornography|amateurs]] and professional pornographic models,<ref name=\"nythow\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ladbible.com/news/interesting-woman-makes-7400-in-three-months-from-selling-her-selfies-online-20190228|title=Woman Makes \u00a33,000 Per Month From Selling Her Selfies Online|website=LAD Bible|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://gcn.ie/beware-malegeneral-site-sharing-private-images-hook-up-apps/|title=Beware Of 'MaleGeneral': A Site Sharing Private Images Sent On Hook Up Apps|last=|first=|date=7 February 2019|website=[[Gay Community News (Dublin)]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/science-tech/article/38717/1/onlyfans-is-the-site-where-porn-is-more-intimate-than-ever| title=OnlyFans is the site where porn is more intimate than ever|website=Dazed|access-date=4 March 2019| date=19 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/jackmackenroth-onlyfans/|title=Behind the paywall of OnlyFans with model Jack Mackenroth|last=|first=|date=19 July 2018|website=[[Gay Star News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref> but is also used by people sharing fitness photos and videos.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ladbible.com/news/viral-former-chef-becomes-millionaire-by-sharing-fitness-photos-on-instagram-20190410|title=Former Chef Becomes Millionaire By Sharing Fitness Photos On Instagram|last=|first=|date=|website=[[LAD Bible]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pornographic video digital distribution platforms|state=expand}}\n\n[[Category:British erotica and pornography websites]]\n[[Category:Companies based in London]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Video hosting]]\n[[Category:Social media companies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|British subscription-only content service}}\n{{Infobox dot-com company\n| name = OnlyFans, Inc.\n| logo = OnlyFans logo 2.jpg\n| screenshot = \n| screenshot_size = <!-- default 300px -->\n| caption = \n| screenshot_alt = is\n| collapsible = no\n| collapsetext = \n| type = Membership platform\n| language = English\n| num_users = 20 million registered users\n| CEO = {{unbulleted list|Timothy Stokely}}\n| location_city = [[London]]\n| location_country = United Kingdom\n| launch_date = {{Start date and age|df=yes|2016}}\n| founder = {{unbulleted list|Timothy Stokely}}\n| alexa = {{increase}} 1,157 {{small|{{nowrap|(Global, {{as of|2020|04|15|alt= April 2020}})}}}}<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url= https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/onlyfans.com | title= Onlyfans.com Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic | publisher= [[Alexa Internet]] |accessdate= 15 April 2020}}</ref>\n| current_status = Active\n}}\n[[File:Logo of OnlyFans since the launch in 2016.png|thumb|Logo of OnlyFans since the launch in 2016]]\n'''OnlyFans''' is a [[social media]] service based in [[London]] UK. Creators run a paid [[Subscription service|subscription content service]], with ways for them to build relationships and provide exclusive content to their [[subscribers]], or \"[[fan (person)|fan]]s\". \n\nIt is popular in the [[adult entertainment]] industry,<ref name=\"nythow\" /> but also hosts content creators from other genres such as [[physical fitness]] experts<ref name=\":1\" /> and other creators who post regularly online. It allows content creators to receive funding directly from their fans on a monthly basis as well as on tips and the [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) feature.<ref name=\"mediapack\">{{cite nonews|last=|first=|url=|title=English: OnlyFans media pack|date=12 February 2019|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}{{full citation needed|date=February 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' commended OnlyFans for helping change adult entertainment work by giving control back to the performers to earn money for the content they create.<ref name=\"nythow\">{{Cite news|last1=Bernstein|first1=Jacob|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/09/style/onlyfans-porn-stars.html|title=How OnlyFans Changed Sex Work Forever|date=9 February 2019|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|access-date=22 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Business model ==\nOnlyFans deliberately lacks restrictive content policy and permits users to share revealing or completely nude pictures of themselves in exchange for a monthly membership fee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pandoramodeling.com/only-fans-for-adult-video-chat-models/|title=OnlyFans Guide For Adult Video Chat Models|website=Pandora Modeling|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref> 80% of the fees collected for each feed go to the content creator, and the remaining 20% percent go to OnlyFans.<ref name=\"nythow\"/> After merchant and processing fees, the company's share is around 12%.<ref name=\"nythow\" />\n\n== History ==\nOnlyFans was launched in 2016 as a website for social media performers to allow their followers to subscribe for a monthly fee to see clips and photos.\nLittle is known about the parent company, Fenix International Limited.<ref name=\"nythow\" />\n\nAs of February 2020, the site has 20 million [[registered user]]s and claims to have paid out $400 million to its 200,000 content creators.<ref name=\"fandeck\">{{cite news |title=English: OnlyFans brand deck |url= |date=8 November 2019}}{{full citation needed|date=February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable creators ===\nIn 2017, [[Courtney Stodden]] urged followers to subscribe to her updates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/courtney-stodden-starts-charging-randy-11493289|title=Courtney Stodden starts charging randy fans to see her nudes|last=Kindon|first=Frances|last2=Duff|first2=Seamus|date=9 November 2017|website=mirror|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref> In 2018 [[Megan Barton Hanson]], a participant in the reality television series [[Love Island (2015 TV series, series 4)|''Love Island'']], posted naked videos of herself online for a monthly subscription.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/showbiz/celebrity-news/love-islands-megan-barton-hanson-12675723|title=Newbie Megan poses for naked videos in an online subscription site|last=Martin|first=Laura|date=10 June 2018|website=irishmirror|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, 20-year-old American Kaylen Ward raised more than $1 million in contributions to [[Charitable organization|charity]] during the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|wild bushfires in Australia]]. OnlyFans teamed with her for their first partnership for a charitable cause.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/the-goods/2020/1/8/21056863/australia-fires-nudes-charity-porn| title=Nude photos raised over $1 million for the Australia fires|website=VOX|access-date=9 January 2020}}</ref> This started a trend with some OnlyFans creators who have been raising money through their accounts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/07/style/kaylen-ward-donations-australia-fires.html| title=Donate $10 to Australia, Get a Nude Photo|website=New York Times|access-date=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Usage ==\nThe website is commonly used by both [[Amateur pornography|amateurs]] and professional pornographic models,<ref name=\"nythow\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ladbible.com/news/interesting-woman-makes-7400-in-three-months-from-selling-her-selfies-online-20190228|title=Woman Makes \u00a33,000 Per Month From Selling Her Selfies Online|website=LAD Bible|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://gcn.ie/beware-malegeneral-site-sharing-private-images-hook-up-apps/|title=Beware Of 'MaleGeneral': A Site Sharing Private Images Sent On Hook Up Apps|last=|first=|date=7 February 2019|website=[[Gay Community News (Dublin)]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/science-tech/article/38717/1/onlyfans-is-the-site-where-porn-is-more-intimate-than-ever| title=OnlyFans is the site where porn is more intimate than ever|website=Dazed|access-date=4 March 2019| date=19 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/jackmackenroth-onlyfans/|title=Behind the paywall of OnlyFans with model Jack Mackenroth|last=|first=|date=19 July 2018|website=[[Gay Star News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 February 2019}}</ref> but is also used by people sharing fitness photos and videos.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ladbible.com/news/viral-former-chef-becomes-millionaire-by-sharing-fitness-photos-on-instagram-20190410|title=Former Chef Becomes Millionaire By Sharing Fitness Photos On Instagram|last=|first=|date=|website=[[LAD Bible]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Pornographic video digital distribution platforms|state=expand}}\n\n[[Category:British erotica and pornography websites]]\n[[Category:Companies based in London]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 2016]]\n[[Category:Video hosting]]\n[[Category:Social media companies]]\n", "name_user": "PointComm", "label": "safe", "comment": "expanded UK", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OnlyFans"}
{"title_page": "William Egerton (1684\u20131732)", "text_new": "{{Other people|William Egerton}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n[[File:Egerton family COA (Dukes of Bridgewater, Dukes of Sutherland).svg|thumb|150px|Arms of Egerton: ''Argent, a lion rampant gules between three [[pheon]]s sable''<ref>Debrett's Peerage, 1968, p. 1077, Duke of Sutherland</ref>]]\n'''William Egerton''' (1684\u20131732) was a British Army officer and Whig politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] almost continuously from 1706 to 1732.\n\n==Early life==\nEgerton was the fourth son of [[John Egerton, 3rd Earl of Bridgwater]] and his wife Jane Paulet, daughter of [[Charles Paulet, 1st Duke of Bolton]]. He travelled abroad in Germany and then joined the army. He was a captain in the [[6th Foot]] in 1704 and  was captain and lieutenant in the [[1st Foot Guards]] from 1705.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/egerton-hon-william-1684-1732| title= EGERTON, Hon. William (1684-1732).| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1690-1715)| accessdate = 23 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nEgerton was returned unopposed as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Buckinghamshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckinghamshire]] at a by-election on 27 February 1706. At the [[1708 British general election]], he  was returned unopposed as Whig MP  for [[Brackley (UK Parliament constituency)|Brackley]]. He was initially inactive in the House as he was serving with the army in Flanders, but voted for the impeachment of Dr Sacheverell in 1710.  He was returned again at the [[1710 British general election]] and voted for the motion of \u2018No Peace without Spain\u2019 and   against the French commerce bill on 18 June 1713. At the [[1713 British general election]] he was   returned in  a contest and on voted against the expulsion of Richard Steele on 18 March 1714. Egerton was said to have spoken insultingly about the Duke of Ormond, and in April 1714 he was told  by Secretary at War, Francis Gwyn,  that the Queen \u2018had no further service for him\u2019 and was to be given 1,000 guineas for his company. He was then unseated on petition on 20 April 1714.<ref name=HOP/>   \n\nAfter the Hanoverian succession Egerton was made [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|Colonel]] of his own infantry regiment, later known as the [[36th Regiment of Foot]]. He was returned unopposed as MP for Brackley at the [[1715 general election]]. In 1719 he was made Colonel of another Regiment, later known as the [[20th Regiment of Foot]]. He was returned unopposed again for Brackley in [[1722 British general election|1722]] and [[1727 British general election|1727]]. He voted with the government on all known occasions.<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url = https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/egerton-hon-william-1684-1732 | title= EGERTON, Hon. William (1684-1732).| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1715-1754)| accessdate = 23 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nEgerton died on 15 July 1732. He had married Anna Maria Saunders, the daughter of [[George Saunders (Royal Navy officer)|Admiral Sir George Saunders]], Commissioner of the Navy, and had three daughters. His daughter Jane married [[Thomas Revell]] MP of [[Fetcham Park House|Fetcham Park]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Robert Dormer (MP)|Robert Dormer]]\n | before2 = [[Richard Temple, 1st Viscount Cobham|Sir Richard Temple, 4th Bt.]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Buckinghamshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckinghamshire]]\n | years =     1706\u2013[[1708 British general election|1708]]\n | with  =  [[Richard Temple, 1st Viscount Cobham|Sir Richard Temple, 4th Bt.]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Edmund Denton, 1st Baronet|Sir Edmund Denton, 1st Bt.]]  \n | after2 = [[Richard Hampden (1674\u20131728)|Richard Hampden]]  \n}}\n\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Harry Mordaunt]]\n | before2 = [[Charles Egerton (MP for Brackley)|Charles Egerton]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Brackley (UK Parliament constituency)|Brackley]]\n | years =   [[1708 British general election|1708]]\u20131714  \n | with  =  [[Charles Egerton (MP for Brackley)|Charles Egerton]]\n | with2 = [[John Burgh (MP for Brackley)|John Burgh]]\n | with3 = [[Paul Methuen (diplomat)|Paul Methuen]] \n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[John Burgh (MP for Brackley)|John Burgh]]\n | after2 = [[Henry Watkins (politician)|Henry Watkins]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[John Burgh (MP for Brackley)|John Burgh]]\n | before2 = [[Henry Watkins (politician)|Henry Watkins]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Brackley (UK Parliament constituency)|Brackley]]\n | years =   [[1715 British general election|1715]]\u2013 1732 \n | with  =  [[Paul Methuen (diplomat)|Sir Paul Methuen]]\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[George Lee (English politician)|Dr George Lee]]\n | after2 = [[Paul Methuen (diplomat)|Sir Paul Methuen]]\n}}\n}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Henry Disney]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Colonel of [[36th (Herefordshire) Regiment of Foot|William Egerton's<br />Regiment of Foot]]|years=1715\u20131719}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sir Charles Hotham, 4th Baronet]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Thomas Meredyth]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Colonel of [[Lancashire Fusiliers|William Egerton's<br />Regiment of Foot]]|years=1719\u20131732}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Francis Howard, 1st Earl of Effingham]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Egerton, William}}\n[[Category:1684 births]]\n[[Category:1732 deaths]]\n[[Category:British Army officers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1705\u20131707]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1707\u20131708]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1708\u20131710]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1710\u20131713]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1713\u20131715]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1715\u20131722]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1722\u20131727]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n\n\n{{England-pre1707-MP-stub}}\n{{England-GreatBritain-MP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|William Egerton}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2017}}\n[[File:Egerton family COA (Dukes of Bridgewater, Dukes of Sutherland).svg|thumb|150px|Arms of Egerton: ''Argent, a lion rampant gules between three [[pheon]]s sable''<ref>Debrett's Peerage, 1968, p. 1077, Duke of Sutherland</ref>]]\n'''Hon. William Egerton''' (1684\u20131732) was a British Army officer and Whig politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] almost continuously from 1706 to 1732.\n\n==Early life==\nEgerton was the fourth son of [[John Egerton, 3rd Earl of Bridgwater]] and his wife Jane Paulet, daughter of [[Charles Paulet, 1st Duke of Bolton]]. He travelled abroad in Germany and then joined the army. He was a captain in the [[6th Foot]] in 1704 and  was captain and lieutenant in the [[1st Foot Guards]] from 1705.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1690-1715/member/egerton-hon-william-1684-1732| title= EGERTON, Hon. William (1684-1732).| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1690-1715)| accessdate = 23 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nEgerton was returned unopposed as [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Buckinghamshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckinghamshire]] at a by-election on 27 February 1706. At the [[1708 British general election]], he  was returned unopposed as Whig MP  for [[Brackley (UK Parliament constituency)|Brackley]]. He was initially inactive in the House as he was serving with the army in Flanders, but voted for the impeachment of Dr Sacheverell in 1710.  He was returned again at the [[1710 British general election]] and voted for the motion of \u2018No Peace without Spain\u2019 and   against the French commerce bill on 18 June 1713. At the [[1713 British general election]] he was   returned in  a contest and on voted against the expulsion of Richard Steele on 18 March 1714. Egerton was said to have spoken insultingly about the Duke of Ormond, and in April 1714 he was told  by Secretary at War, Francis Gwyn,  that the Queen \u2018had no further service for him\u2019 and was to be given 1,000 guineas for his company. He was then unseated on petition on 20 April 1714.<ref name=HOP/>   \n\nAfter the Hanoverian succession Egerton was made [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|Colonel]] of his own infantry regiment, later known as the [[36th Regiment of Foot]]. He was returned unopposed as MP for Brackley at the [[1715 general election]]. In 1719 he was made Colonel of another Regiment, later known as the [[20th Regiment of Foot]]. He was returned unopposed again for Brackley in [[1722 British general election|1722]] and [[1727 British general election|1727]]. He voted with the government on all known occasions.<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url = https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/egerton-hon-william-1684-1732 | title= EGERTON, Hon. William (1684-1732).| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1715-1754)| accessdate = 23 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nEgerton died on 15 July 1732. He had married Anna Maria Saunders, the daughter of [[George Saunders (Royal Navy officer)|Admiral Sir George Saunders]], Commissioner of the Navy, and had three daughters. His daughter Jane married [[Thomas Revell]] MP of [[Fetcham Park House|Fetcham Park]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Robert Dormer (MP)|Robert Dormer]]\n | before2 = [[Richard Temple, 1st Viscount Cobham|Sir Richard Temple, 4th Bt.]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Buckinghamshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckinghamshire]]\n | years =     1706\u2013[[1708 British general election|1708]]\n | with  =  [[Richard Temple, 